Appendix B: Martian Regolith Composite Material Properties Database

B.1 Processed Material Specifications
Data derived from terrestrial testing of Mars regolith simulants (e.g., MGS-1, JSC Mars-1A) with proposed binders.

Material Formation Process Compressive Strength (MPa) Tensile Strength (MPa) Density (kg/m³) Optimal Use Case
Microwave-Sintered Basalt 2.45 GHz, 1200°C, 85% melt 80 - 110 8 - 12 2,800 - 3,000 Primary tunnel liner, structural arches
Sulfur Concrete 40% Martian Sulfur, 60% Regolith 20 - 35 4 - 7 2,000 - 2,200 Floor slabs, non-load-bearing walls
Regolith-Polyethylene Composite 15-20% PE binder, hot-pressed 30 - 50 10 - 15 1,800 - 2,000 Pre-fab arch segments, utility conduits
Compacted Regolith (Reference) In-situ, >95% density 0.5 - 2.0 ~0.1 1,600 - 1,800 Backfill, radiation shielding

B.2 In-Situ Binder Production Parameters

· Process: Reverse Water-Gas Shift (RWGS) + Polymerization.
  1. CO₂ + H₂ → CO + H₂O (RWGS, ~400°C)
  2. 2CO + 4H₂ → C₂H₄ + 2H₂O (Fischer-Tropsch variant)
  3. nC₂H₄ → (C₂H₄)n (Polymerization to Polyethylene)
· Requirements per kg Polyethylene: 3.14 kg CO₂, 0.43 kg H₂ (from 3.9 kg H₂O electrolysis).
· M-ARES Reactor Scale: Designed for 1-2 kg/day production, sufficient for 5-10 m³ of composite daily.

B.3 Excavation Torque & Force Requirements
Empirical models based on terrestrial and lunar analog testing, scaled for Martian gravity (0.38g) and soil mechanics.

· Specific Energy of Excavation (e): 2.5 ± 0.5 kWh/m³ for dense, consolidated regolith at 5m depth.
· Required Cutting Force (F_c): F_c = k * σ * d * w where:
  · k = tool factor (0.8 for tungsten carbide)
  · σ = regolith shear strength (~5 kPa for compacted layer)
  · d = cutting depth (0.05 m per pass)
  · w = drum width (0.4 m)
  · F_c ≈ 80 N per cutting tooth.
· Total Drum Torque (T): T = F_c * n * r where n = engaged teeth (6), r = drum radius (0.2 m).
  · T ≈ 96 Nm per drum. Dual counter-rotating drums require ~200 Nm continuous, within the 500 Nm capability of the uprated motors.

